# Control Flow
Control flow statements break up the flow of execution by employing decision making, looping, and branching.

### If-Else
```java
if (score >= 90) {
    System.out.println("A");
} else if (score >= 80) {
    System.out.println("B");
} else {
    System.out.println("C");
}
```

### Switch Statement (Java 14+ Enhanced)
```java
String dayType = switch (day) {
    case MONDAY, TUESDAY, WEDNESDAY, THURSDAY, FRIDAY -> "Weekday";
    case SATURDAY, SUNDAY -> "Weekend";
    default -> throw new IllegalArgumentException("Invalid day");
};
```

### Loops
- **For Loop**: `for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) { ... }`
- **Enhanced For-Each**: `for (String name : names) { ... }`
- **While Loop**: `while (condition) { ... }`
- **Do-While Loop**: `do { ... } while (condition);`

# Arrays
An array is a container object that holds a fixed number of values of a single type.

### Declaration and Initialization
```java
// 1D Array
int[] numbers = new int[5];
int[] primes = {2, 3, 5, 7, 11};

// 2D Array
int[][] matrix = new int[3][3];
int[][] grid = { {1, 2}, {3, 4} };
```

### Iterating over Arrays
```java
for(int i=0; i<primes.length; i++) {
    System.out.println(primes[i]);
}
```

# Strings
Strings in Java are objects that are backed internally by a char array (or byte array in newer versions).

### The String Pool
Strings are **immutable**. When you create a String literal, it is cached in the String Pool in the Heap memory to save space.

```mermaid
graph LR;
    Stack[Stack] -->|str1, str2 reference| Pool[String Pool: 'Hello'];
```

```java
String str1 = "Hello";
String str2 = "Hello";
System.out.println(str1 == str2); // true (same reference in pool)

String str3 = new String("Hello");
System.out.println(str1 == str3); // false (str3 is a new object in heap)
System.out.println(str1.equals(str3)); // true (same value)
```

# Mutable Strings
Since `String` is immutable, modifying it creates a new object every time. Use `StringBuilder` or `StringBuffer` for mutable strings.

### StringBuilder
Fast, but **not thread-safe**.
```java
StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder("Hello");
sb.append(" World");
System.out.println(sb.toString());
```

### StringBuffer
Slower, but **thread-safe** (synchronized).
```java
StringBuffer sbf = new StringBuffer("Hello");
sbf.append(" Safe World");
```

# Classes & Objects
- **Class**: A blueprint for creating objects.
- **Object**: An instance of a class.

### Memory Visualization
When you use `new`, memory is allocated on the **Heap**. The reference variable is stored on the **Stack**.

```mermaid
graph LR;
    Stack[Stack Memory: Car myCar] -->|References| Heap[Heap Memory: Car Object {color, speed}];
```

### Example
```java
public class Car {
    String color; // Instance variable

    public Car(String color) { // Constructor
        this.color = color;
    }

    public void drive() { // Method
        System.out.println("Driving a " + color + " car.");
    }
}

// Usage
Car myCar = new Car("Red");
myCar.drive();
```

# Inheritance & Polymorphism

### Inheritance (`extends`)
Java supports single class inheritance. A subclass inherits non-private members of its superclass.

```java
class Animal {
    void eat() { System.out.println("Eating..."); }
}
class Dog extends Animal {
    void bark() { System.out.println("Barking..."); }
}
```

### Polymorphism
- **Compile-time (Method Overloading)**: Same method name, different parameters.
- **Runtime (Method Overriding)**: Subclass provides a specific implementation of a method defined in its superclass using `@Override`.

```java
class Cat extends Animal {
    @Override
    void eat() {
        System.out.println("Cat is eating fish...");
    }
}

Animal myAnimal = new Cat();
myAnimal.eat(); // Output: Cat is eating fish...
```

# Abstraction in Java

### Abstract Classes
- Can have both abstract (no body) and concrete methods.
- Cannot be instantiated directly.
- Can have state (instance variables).

```java
abstract class Shape {
    abstract void draw();
}
```

### Interfaces (`implements`)
- A contract that classes must follow.
- Methods are implicitly `public abstract` (prior to Java 8).
- Java 8 introduced `default` and `static` methods in interfaces.
- A class can implement multiple interfaces.

```java
interface Drawable {
    void draw();
    default void printInfo() {
        System.out.println("This is a drawable object.");
    }
}
```

# Exception Hierarchy
```mermaid
graph TD;
    A[Throwable] --> B[Error];
    A --> C[Exception];
    C --> D[RuntimeException (Unchecked)];
    C --> E[IOException (Checked)];
```

- **Error**: Irrecoverable conditions (e.g. OutOfMemoryError).
- **Checked Exceptions**: Must be handled or declared (`throws`). Checked at compile-time.
- **Unchecked Exceptions**: Extend RuntimeException. Checked at runtime (e.g. NullPointerException).

# Handling Exceptions

### Example
```java
try {
    int result = 10 / 0;
} catch (ArithmeticException e) {
    System.out.println("Cannot divide by zero!");
} finally {
    System.out.println("Execution complete.");
}
```

### Try-with-Resources (Java 7+)
Automatically closes resources that implement `AutoCloseable`.
```java
try (BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader("file.txt"))) {
    System.out.println(br.readLine());
} catch (IOException e) {
    e.printStackTrace();
}
```

# Creating Custom Exceptions
You can create your own exception classes by extending `Exception` or `RuntimeException`.

```java
public class InvalidAgeException extends Exception {
    public InvalidAgeException(String message) {
        super(message);
    }
}

// Usage
public void checkAge(int age) throws InvalidAgeException {
    if (age < 18) {
        throw new InvalidAgeException("Age must be 18 or older.");
    }
}
```

# Lists
Ordered collections that allow duplicates.

### ArrayList
Backed by a dynamic array. Fast random access `O(1)`, slow insertion/deletion in middle `O(n)`.
```java
List<String> list = new ArrayList<>();
list.add("Apple");
list.add("Banana");
```

### LinkedList
Backed by a doubly-linked list. Fast insertion/deletion `O(1)`, slow random access `O(n)`.
```java
List<String> list = new LinkedList<>();
list.add("Apple");
```

# Maps
Key-Value pairs. Keys must be unique.

### HashMap
Fast `O(1)` operations. Uses a hash table internally.

```mermaid
graph LR;
    Key[Key] -->|hashCode| Hash[Hash Function];
    Hash --> Index[Array Index];
    Index --> Bucket[Bucket Node containing Key, Value, Next];
```

```java
Map<String, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
map.put("Alice", 25);
map.put("Bob", 30);
```

### TreeMap
Sorted by keys in natural order. `O(log n)` operations.

# Generics

### Generic Class
```java
class Box<T> {
    private T item;
    public void setItem(T item) { this.item = item; }
    public T getItem() { return item; }
}

Box<String> stringBox = new Box<>();
stringBox.setItem("Hello");
```

### Generic Method
```java
public <T> void printArray(T[] array) {
    for (T element : array) {
        System.out.println(element);
    }
}
```

# Bounds & Wildcards

### Upper Bounded Wildcards
Restricts the unknown type to be a specific type or a subtype of that type.
```java
public void processShapes(List<? extends Shape> shapes) {
    for (Shape s : shapes) {
        s.draw();
    }
}
```

### Lower Bounded Wildcards
Restricts the unknown type to be a specific type or a super type of that type.
```java
public void addIntegers(List<? super Integer> list) {
    list.add(5);
}
```

# Thread Lifecycle
```mermaid
graph LR;
    New -->|start| Runnable;
    Runnable -->|scheduler| Running;
    Running -->|sleep/wait| Blocked;
    Blocked -->|notify| Runnable;
    Running -->|finish| Terminated;
```

### Creating a Thread
1. Extending `Thread` class.
2. Implementing `Runnable` interface (Preferred).

```java
class MyTask implements Runnable {
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Running in thread: " + Thread.currentThread().getName());
    }
}

Thread t1 = new Thread(new MyTask());
t1.start();
```

# Synchronization
Used to prevent thread interference (Race Conditions).

### Synchronized Method
```java
public synchronized void increment() {
    count++;
}
```

### Synchronized Block
Provides finer granularity.
```java
public void process() {
    synchronized(this) {
        // critical section
    }
}
```

### ReentrantLock
Provides more flexibility than intrinsic locks.
```java
Lock lock = new ReentrantLock();
lock.lock();
try {
    // critical section
} finally {
    lock.unlock();
}
```

# Thread Pools
Creating new threads is expensive. Thread pools manage a pool of worker threads.

### ExecutorService
```java
ExecutorService executor = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(5);
for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
    executor.submit(() -> {
        System.out.println("Task executed by " + Thread.currentThread().getName());
    });
}
executor.shutdown();
```

# Lambdas
A short block of code which takes in parameters and returns a value. Used to implement functional interfaces (interfaces with exactly one abstract method).

```java
// Before Java 8
Runnable r1 = new Runnable() {
    @Override
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Running");
    }
};

// Java 8 Lambda
Runnable r2 = () -> System.out.println("Running");
```

### Common Functional Interfaces
- `Predicate<T>`: Returns boolean.
- `Consumer<T>`: Accepts an argument, returns nothing.
- `Function<T, R>`: Accepts an argument, returns a result.
- `Supplier<T>`: Takes nothing, returns a result.

# Optional
A container object which may or may not contain a non-null value. Helps prevent `NullPointerException`.

```java
Optional<String> opt = Optional.ofNullable(getName());

// If value is present, print it
opt.ifPresent(name -> System.out.println(name));

// Provide a default value
String name = opt.orElse("Unknown");

// Throw exception if empty
String strictName = opt.orElseThrow(() -> new IllegalArgumentException("Name is required"));
```
